    '<|logic|>What is the time complexity of binary search?<|assistant|Binary search has O(log n) time complexity. Here is why: each comparison cuts the search space in half. Starting with n elements: after 1 step you have n/2, after 2 steps n/4, after k steps n/2^k. The search ends when n/2^k = 1, so k = log2(n). This means even for a billion elements, you need at most 30 comparisons. The space complexity is O(1) for iterative implementation and O(log n) for recursive due to the call stack.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Explain the difference between BFS and DFS<|assistant|BFS (Breadth-First Search) explores all neighbors at the current depth before moving deeper. Uses a queue (FIFO). Finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. Space: O(w) where w is max width.\n\nDFS (Depth-First Search) goes as deep as possible before backtracking. Uses a stack (LIFO) or recursion. Finds paths quickly but not necessarily shortest. Space: O(h) where h is max depth.\n\nWhen to use BFS: shortest path, level-order traversal, finding connected components.\nWhen to use DFS: topological sorting, cycle detection, maze solving, finding all paths.\n\nBoth have O(V+E) time complexity. The key difference is exploration order.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>What is dynamic programming and when should I use it?<|assistant|Dynamic programming solves problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems and storing results to avoid recomputation. Two approaches:\n\n1. Top-down (memoization): Write recursive solution, cache results.\n2. Bottom-up (tabulation): Solve smallest subproblems first, build up.\n\nUse DP when the problem has:\n- Optimal substructure: optimal solution contains optimal sub-solutions\n- Overlapping subproblems: same subproblems are solved repeatedly\n\nClassic problems:\n- Fibonacci: O(2^n) naive, O(n) with DP\n- Knapsack: O(n*W) with DP\n- Longest Common Subsequence: O(m*n)\n- Edit Distance: O(m*n)\n\nThe key insight: if you are recomputing the same thing, you should cache it.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Explain Big O notation with examples<|assistant|Big O describes the upper bound of how an algorithm scales with input size:\n\nO(1) - Constant: array access by index, hash lookup\nO(log n) - Logarithmic: binary search, balanced tree operations\nO(n) - Linear: scanning an array, linear search\nO(n log n) - Linearithmic: merge sort, heap sort\nO(n^2) - Quadratic: nested loops, bubble sort\nO(2^n) - Exponential: recursive Fibonacci, subset generation\nO(n!) - Factorial: generating all permutations\n\nKey rules:\n- Drop constants: O(2n) = O(n)\n- Drop lower terms: O(n^2 + n) = O(n^2)\n- Different inputs = different variables: O(a + b) not O(n)\n\nAlways analyze the worst case unless specified otherwise.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>How do hash tables work and what causes collisions?<|assistant|Hash tables map keys to array indices using a hash function: index = hash(key) % capacity.\n\nAverage case: O(1) for insert, lookup, delete.\nWorst case: O(n) if all keys hash to the same index.\n\nCollisions happen when two different keys produce the same index. Solutions:\n\n1. Chaining: each bucket holds a linked list of entries. Simple but uses extra memory.\n2. Open addressing: if slot taken, probe for next empty slot. Linear probing (i+1, i+2...), quadratic probing (i+1, i+4, i+9...), or double hashing.\n3. Robin Hood hashing: steal from richer buckets to reduce variance.\n\nLoad factor = items / capacity. When it exceeds 0.7-0.75, resize and rehash. Good hash functions distribute keys uniformly to minimize collisions.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Explain the two-pointer technique<|assistant|The two-pointer technique uses two indices to traverse data efficiently:\n\n1. Opposite direction (left/right pointers):\n   - Check if string is palindrome\n   - Two sum in sorted array\n   - Container with most water\n\n2. Same direction (fast/slow pointers):\n   - Remove duplicates from sorted array\n   - Find middle of linked list\n   - Detect cycle in linked list\n\nExample - Two Sum in sorted array:\ndef two_sum(arr, target):\n    left, right = 0, len(arr) - 1\n    while left < right:\n        s = arr[left] + arr[right]\n        if s == target: return [left, right]\n        elif s < target: left += 1\n        else: right -= 1\n    return []\n\nTime: O(n), Space: O(1). Much better than nested loops O(n^2).<|end|>',

    "<|logic|>What is the difference between a stack and a queue?<|assistant|Stack: LIFO (Last In, First Out). Think of a stack of plates.\n- Push: add to top - O(1)\n- Pop: remove from top - O(1)\n- Peek: view top - O(1)\n- Use cases: undo/redo, function call stack, DFS, expression evaluation\n\nQueue: FIFO (First In, First Out). Think of a line at a store.\n- Enqueue: add to back - O(1)\n- Dequeue: remove from front - O(1)\n- Front: view front - O(1)\n- Use cases: BFS, task scheduling, print queue, message queues\n\nPriority Queue: elements dequeued by priority, not order of arrival.\n- Use cases: Dijkstra's algorithm, A* search, job scheduling\n\nIn Python: use list for stack, collections.deque for queue. In Java: Stack class, LinkedList as Queue.<|end|>",

    "<|logic|>How does Dijkstra's algorithm work?<|assistant|Dijkstra's finds the shortest path from a source to all other nodes in a weighted graph with non-negative edges.\n\nAlgorithm:\n1. Set distance to source = 0, all others = infinity\n2. Visit the unvisited node with smallest distance\n3. For each unvisited neighbor, calculate tentative distance through current node\n4. If tentative < known distance, update it\n5. Mark current node as visited, repeat from step 2\n\nWith a priority queue: O((V + E) log V)\nWithout: O(V^2)\n\nKey insight: once a node is visited, its shortest distance is finalized. This only works with non-negative weights. For negative weights, use Bellman-Ford instead.<|end|>",

    "<|logic|>What is a graph and what are common representations?<|assistant|A graph is a set of vertices (nodes) connected by edges. Types:\n\n- Undirected: edges have no direction (friendship)\n- Directed: edges have direction (following)\n- Weighted: edges have costs (distance)\n- Unweighted: edges have no costs\n\nRepresentations:\n\n1. Adjacency Matrix: 2D array, matrix[i][j] = 1 if edge exists. O(V^2) space. Fast edge lookup O(1). Slow neighbor iteration O(V).\n\n2. Adjacency List: dict of lists, graph[i] = [neighbors]. O(V+E) space. Slow edge lookup O(degree). Fast neighbor iteration.\n\n3. Edge List: list of (u, v, weight) tuples. O(E) space. Used in Kruskal's algorithm.\n\nUse adjacency list for sparse graphs (most real-world graphs). Use matrix for dense graphs or when you need fast edge lookups.<|end|>",

    '<|logic|>Explain the sliding window technique<|assistant|Sliding window maintains a window of elements that slides across data to find optimal subarrays/substrings.\n\nTwo types:\n1. Fixed-size window: window size k stays constant\n2. Variable-size window: window grows/shrinks based on conditions\n\nFixed example - Max sum subarray of size k:\ndef max_sum_k(arr, k):\n    window_sum = sum(arr[:k])\n    max_sum = window_sum\n    for i in range(k, len(arr)):\n        window_sum += arr[i] - arr[i-k]\n        max_sum = max(max_sum, window_sum)\n    return max_sum\n\nVariable example - Longest substring with at most k distinct chars uses two pointers that expand and shrink.\n\nTime complexity: O(n) instead of O(n*k) or O(n^2) for brute force. The key insight is reusing computation from the previous window position.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Explain the greedy algorithm paradigm<|assistant|Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping it leads to a globally optimal solution.\n\nKey properties needed:\n1. Greedy choice property: local optimal leads to global optimal\n2. Optimal substructure: optimal solution contains optimal sub-solutions\n\nWhen greedy works:\n- Activity selection: always pick the earliest-ending activity\n- Huffman coding: always merge two smallest frequencies\n- Dijkstra: always visit closest unvisited node\n- Kruskal: always add smallest edge that does not form cycle\n- Fractional knapsack: always take highest value/weight ratio\n\nWhen greedy fails:\n- 0/1 knapsack: taking the best ratio item may block a better combination\n- Traveling salesman: nearest neighbor can lead to suboptimal tour\n- Longest path: local choices do not guarantee global optimum\n\nProof strategies: exchange argument, stay-ahead argument, or contradiction.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Compare merge sort and quicksort<|assistant|Merge Sort:\n- Divide array in half, sort each, merge\n- Always O(n log n) - guaranteed\n- Stable sort (preserves order of equal elements)\n- O(n) extra space\n- Good for linked lists and external sorting\n- Sequential access pattern - cache-unfriendly\n\nQuicksort:\n- Pick pivot, partition around it, recurse\n- Average O(n log n), worst O(n^2)\n- Not stable (can change order of equal elements)\n- O(log n) stack space (in-place partitioning)\n- Good for arrays with random access\n- Cache-friendly due to locality of reference\n\nPractical choice: quicksort is usually faster in practice due to cache efficiency. Python uses Timsort (merge+insertion hybrid). Most standard libraries use introsort (quicksort that switches to heapsort when recursion is too deep).<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>What is amortized analysis?<|assistant|Amortized analysis averages the cost of operations over a sequence, even if individual operations are expensive.\n\nThree methods:\n\n1. Aggregate method: total cost of n operations / n\n   Example: dynamic array insertion. Most insertions are O(1), but resizing is O(n). Over n insertions, total work is O(n), so amortized cost per insertion is O(1).\n\n2. Accounting method: assign different charges to operations\n   Cheap operations save credits for expensive ones.\n   Example: each insert charges 3 units. 1 for the insert, 2 saved for future resize.\n\n3. Potential method: define potential function Phi on data structure state\n   Amortized cost = actual cost + Phi(after) - Phi(before)\n   Example: Phi = 2 * size - capacity for dynamic arrays.\n\nKey insight: amortized O(1) does not mean every operation is O(1). It means the average over many operations is O(1). Real-time systems may need worst-case guarantees instead.<|end|>',

    '<|logic|>Explain backtracking with an example<|assistant|Backtracking systematically tries all possibilities, abandoning paths that cannot lead to a solution.\n\nAlgorithm pattern:\ndef backtrack(state, choices):\n    if is_solution(state):\n        record(state)\n        return\n    for choice in choices:\n        if is_valid(state, choice):\n            apply(state, choice)\n            backtrack(state, remaining_choices)\n            undo(state, choice)  # backtrack\n\nN-Queens example:\ndef solve_n_queens(n):\n    result = []\n    def backtrack(row, cols, diag1, diag2, board):\n        if row == n:\n            result.append(board[:])\n            return\n        for col in range(n):\n            if col in cols or row-col in diag1 or row+col in diag2:\n                continue\n            board[row] = col\n            backtrack(row+1, cols|{col}, diag1|{row-col}, diag2|{row+col}, board)\n            board[row] = -1\n    backtrack(0, set(), set(), set(), [-1]*n)\n    return result\n\nTime: O(n!) in worst case. Pruning with validity checks dramatically reduces the search space. Used in puzzles, combinatorics, and constraint satisfaction.<|end|>',

    "<|logic|>What is a minimum spanning tree?<|assistant|A Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) connects all vertices in a weighted undirected graph with minimum total edge weight.\n\nProperties:\n- Has exactly V-1 edges (V = number of vertices)\n- No cycles (it is a tree)\n- Not necessarily unique (multiple MSTs with same total weight possible)\n\nKruskal's algorithm O(E log E):\n1. Sort all edges by weight\n2. For each edge, if it connects two different components, add it\n3. Use Union-Find to efficiently check components\n\nPrim's algorithm O(E log V) with priority queue:\n1. Start from any vertex\n2. Always add the cheapest edge connecting tree to non-tree vertex\n3. Repeat until all vertices are in the tree\n\nWhen to use which: Kruskal is better for sparse graphs. Prim is better for dense graphs. Both produce the same MST weight.<|end|>",

    '<|logic|>Explain the knapsack problem variants<|assistant|0/1 Knapsack: each item can be taken at most once.\ndef knapsack_01(weights, values, capacity):\n    n = len(weights)\n    dp = [[0] * (capacity + 1) for _ in range(n + 1)]\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        for w in range(capacity + 1):\n            dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]\n            if weights[i-1] <= w:\n                dp[i][w] = max(dp[i][w], dp[i-1][w-weights[i-1]] + values[i-1])\n    return dp[n][capacity]\n\nTime: O(n*W), Space: O(n*W) or O(W) with optimization.\n\nFractional Knapsack: can take fractions of items. Greedy works.\nSort items by value/weight ratio, take as much as possible starting from highest ratio. Time: O(n log n).\n\nUnbounded Knapsack: unlimited copies of each item.\nChange dp[i-1] to dp[i] in the recurrence. Can use the same item multiple times.\n\n0/1 requires DP. Fractional is greedy. Unbounded is DP with slight modification.<|end|>',

