    '<|debugger|>Find the bug in this Python code: def add(a, b): a + b<|assistant|The function is missing a return statement. Currently it computes a + b but discards the result and returns None.\n\nBug:\ndef add(a, b): a + b  # Returns None\n\nFix:\ndef add(a, b): return a + b  # Returns the sum\n\nThis is one of the most common Python mistakes. An expression on its own line is evaluated but its result is thrown away. You must explicitly use return to send a value back to the caller.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def remove_items(lst, item): for i in lst: if i == item: lst.remove(i)<|assistant|The bug is modifying a list while iterating over it. When you remove an element, all subsequent elements shift left, but the iterator moves forward. This causes elements to be skipped.\n\nExample of the bug:\nlst = [1, 2, 2, 3, 4]\nfor i in lst:\n    if i == 2: lst.remove(i)\n# Result: [1, 2, 3, 4] - one 2 was skipped!\n\nFix 1 - List comprehension (best):\nlst = [x for x in lst if x != item]\n\nFix 2 - Iterate over a copy:\nfor i in lst[:]:  # lst[:] creates a copy\n    if i == item: lst.remove(i)\n\nFix 3 - Filter:\nlst = list(filter(lambda x: x != item, lst))\n\nAlways create a new list or iterate over a copy when removing items.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def counter(): count = 0 def increment(): count += 1 return count return increment<|assistant|The bug is trying to modify a variable from an outer scope without declaring it nonlocal. Python treats count += 1 as creating a new local variable, but since it reads count first, you get an UnboundLocalError.\n\nBug:\ndef counter():\n    count = 0\n    def increment():\n        count += 1  # UnboundLocalError!\n        return count\n    return increment\n\nFix:\ndef counter():\n    count = 0\n    def increment():\n        nonlocal count  # Tell Python this is the outer variable\n        count += 1\n        return count\n    return increment\n\nThe nonlocal keyword tells Python to look in the enclosing scope. Without it, Python assumes count is local to increment().<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug in this JavaScript: for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) { setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); }<|assistant|The bug is using var instead of let. var has function scope, so all three timeouts share the same i variable. By the time they execute, i is 3.\n\nBug output: 3, 3, 3 (not 0, 1, 2 as expected)\n\nFix 1 - Use let (block scope):\nfor (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);\n}\n// Output: 0, 1, 2\n\nFix 2 - IIFE to create closure (older approach):\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  (function(j) {\n    setTimeout(() => console.log(j), 100);\n  })(i);\n}\n\nAlways use let/const in for loops. var is function-scoped and causes this classic closure bug.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: class Node: def __init__(self, val): self.val = val self.next = None class LinkedList: def __init__(self): self.head = None def add(self, val): new = Node(val) new.next = self.head self.head = new def print_list(self): curr = self.head while curr: print(curr.val) curr = curr.next<|assistant|The code looks mostly correct for a basic linked list, but the formatting is broken - the class body is all on one line, which Python cannot parse. Each statement needs its own line with proper indentation.\n\nAdditionally, there are potential issues to watch for:\n1. No __str__ or __repr__ method for debugging\n2. No delete method (common need)\n3. No length tracking (O(n) to get size)\n4. The add method prepends (adds to front) - make sure this is the intended behavior\n\nFixed formatting:\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, val):\n        self.val = val\n        self.next = None\n\nclass LinkedList:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.head = None\n    \n    def add(self, val):\n        new = Node(val)\n        new.next = self.head\n        self.head = new\n    \n    def print_list(self):\n        curr = self.head\n        while curr:\n            print(curr.val)\n            curr = curr.next\n\nPython indentation is not cosmetic - it defines code blocks. Always use proper formatting.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def get_value(d, key): return d[key]<|assistant|The bug is that accessing a dictionary with d[key] raises KeyError if the key does not exist. This will crash your program.\n\nBug:\ndef get_value(d, key):\n    return d[key]  # KeyError if key missing!\n\nFix 1 - Use get() with default:\ndef get_value(d, key, default=None):\n    return d.get(key, default)\n\nFix 2 - Check if key exists:\ndef get_value(d, key):\n    if key in d:\n        return d[key]\n    return None\n\nFix 3 - Try/except (Pythonic for expected keys):\ndef get_value(d, key):\n    try:\n        return d[key]\n    except KeyError:\n        return None\n\nThe get() method is usually the cleanest approach. Only use try/except if you expect the key to usually exist.<|end|>',

