    '<|reasoning|>How would you implement a rate limiter?<|assistant|Let me analyze the approaches and tradeoffs.\n\nThree main algorithms:\n\n1. Token Bucket: Tokens are added at a fixed rate. Each request consumes a token. If no tokens available, reject. Allows bursts up to bucket capacity. Best for APIs that need to handle bursts.\n\n2. Leaky Bucket: Requests enter a queue and are processed at a fixed rate. Excess requests are dropped. Smooths traffic to a constant rate. Best for streaming.\n\n3. Sliding Window: Count requests in a time window. Reset counter when window expires. Simple but has boundary issues. Sliding Window Log fixes this by tracking individual request timestamps.\n\nimport time\n\nclass TokenBucket:\n    def __init__(self, rate, capacity):\n        self.rate = rate          # tokens per second\n        self.capacity = capacity  # max tokens\n        self.tokens = capacity\n        self.last_time = time.time()\n    \n    def allow(self):\n        now = time.time()\n        self.tokens = min(self.capacity,\n            self.tokens + (now - self.last_time) * self.rate)\n        self.last_time = now\n        if self.tokens >= 1:\n            self.tokens -= 1\n            return True\n        return False\n\nFor distributed systems, use Redis with atomic operations. For per-user limits, key by user ID.<|end|>',

    "<|reasoning|>How would you find the longest palindromic substring?<|assistant|Let me think about the approaches from simple to optimal.\n\nApproach 1: Check every substring. O(n^3) time. Too slow.\nApproach 2: Expand around center. O(n^2) time, O(1) space. Practical and efficient.\nApproach 3: Manacher's algorithm. O(n) time. Complex but optimal.\n\nThe expand-around-center approach is the best balance of simplicity and efficiency:\n\ndef longest_palindrome(s):\n    if not s: return ''\n    start, max_len = 0, 1\n    \n    def expand(left, right):\n        while left >= 0 and right < len(s) and s[left] == s[right]:\n            left -= 1\n            right += 1\n        return left + 1, right - left - 1\n    \n    for i in range(len(s)):\n        # Odd length palindrome (single center)\n        l1, len1 = expand(i, i)\n        # Even length palindrome (double center)\n        l2, len2 = expand(i, i + 1)\n        l, length = (l1, len1) if len1 > len2 else (l2, len2)\n        if length > max_len:\n            start, max_len = l, length\n    \n    return s[start:start + max_len]\n\nFor each position, expand outward while characters match. Check both odd and even length palindromes. O(n^2) worst case, but often much faster in practice.<|end|>",

