    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: for i in range(10): print(i) if i == 5: break<|assistant|The bug is a SyntaxError. In Python, you cannot put an if statement on the same line after a print() call in a for loop like that without a semicolon or proper indentation. The correct code is:\nfor i in range(10):\n    print(i)\n    if i == 5:\n        break\n\nPython requires proper indentation for block statements. The one-liner version would be: for i in range(10):\n    if i == 5: break\n    print(i) (if you want to skip 5 and not print it).<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: x = [1, 2, 3]\nfor item in x:\n    x.remove(item)<|assistant|The bug is modifying a list while iterating over it. When you remove item 1 at index 0, item 2 shifts to index 0, but the iterator moves to index 1 (which is now 3). So 2 gets skipped entirely. The result is [2] instead of []. Fix: iterate over a copy with for item in x[:]: or use a list comprehension: x = [item for item in x if condition]. This is one of the most common Python bugs.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def factorial(n): return n * factorial(n-1)<|assistant|The bug is a missing base case, causing infinite recursion and a RecursionError. factorial(5) calls factorial(4) calls factorial(3) and so on forever (actually into negative numbers). Fix: add a base case: def factorial(n): return 1 if n <= 1 else n * factorial(n-1). Every recursive function must have a base case that stops the recursion. Without it, Python hits the recursion limit (default 1000) and raises RecursionError.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def get_avg(lst): return sum(lst) / len(lst)<|assistant|Two bugs: 1) Division by zero when lst is empty. len([]) is 0, causing ZeroDivisionError. 2) The function does not validate input type. Fix: def get_avg(lst):\n    if not lst:\n        return 0  # or None, or raise ValueError\n    return sum(lst) / len(lst). Always handle edge cases like empty collections. Consider also handling non-numeric types with a try/except for TypeError.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: class Counter:\n    count = 0\n    def increment(self):\n        count += 1<|assistant|The bug is an UnboundLocalError. The increment method tries to modify count, but Python treats count as a local variable because of the += assignment. You need to declare it as a class variable using Counter.count or self.__class__.count. The fix: def increment(self): Counter.count += 1. Alternatively, use an instance variable: self.count = 0 in __init__ and self.count += 1 in increment. Class variables are shared across all instances; instance variables are per-instance.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: import copy\na = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]\nb = copy.copy(a)\nb[0][0] = 99\nprint(a[0][0])<|assistant|The bug is that copy.copy() creates a shallow copy, so the inner lists are still shared references. b[0] and a[0] point to the same list object. Modifying b[0][0] also modifies a[0][0], so a[0][0] becomes 99. Fix: use copy.deepcopy(a) which recursively copies all nested objects. Shallow copy is like photocopying a document that has sticky notes - the copy has the same sticky notes pointing to the same original notes. Deep copy duplicates everything.<|end|>',

    '<|debugger|>Find the bug: def remove_negatives(lst):\n    for i, val in enumerate(lst):\n        if val < 0:\n            del lst[i]<|assistant|The bug is deleting elements while iterating forward with enumerate. After deleting an element at index i, all subsequent elements shift left, but the index i+1 is now the element that was at i+2, causing elements to be skipped. Fix: iterate backwards: for i in range(len(lst)-1, -1, -1): if lst[i] < 0: del lst[i]. Or use a list comprehension: lst[:] = [x for x in lst if x >= 0]. The backwards iteration ensures deletion does not affect unvisited indices.<|end|>',

